    app
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>We are now ready to run our tests. Execute the following commands.</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">pytest</code></p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">coverage run -m pytest</code></p>

<p>To view the coverage report on the terminal, run:</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">coverage report</code></p>

<p>Note that the above are mostly finished artifacts. In the development process,
after writing the tests, one would generally add some code, test the
implementaion bit by bit, add some more tests and so on until all the tests
passâ€¦I hope you get the picture.</p>

<p>This is generally what <a href="https://code.tutsplus.com/tutorials/beginning-test-driven-development-in-python--net-30137" target="_blank">Test Driven Development</a> entails. You write tests that you expect will fail,
make the tests pass, refactor, rinse repeat. The tests become an integral part
of your development process, not just an annoying afterthought.</p>

